definition.value: An amino trisaccharide consisting of a 2-acetamido-beta-D-mannopyranose residue and two alpha-D-glucopyranose residues joined together in sequence by (1->4)-glycosidic bonds.
A glycosyllgalactose that is the 6-O-fucoside of alpha-D-galactopyranoside.

An amino pentasaccharide that is 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-6-O-sulfo-D-glucitol which has been glycosylated at positions 3 and 4 by 6-deoxy-alpha-L-galactopyranosyl and 6-O-sulfo-beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->4)-2-acetamido-2-deoxy-6-O-sulfo-beta-D-glucopyranosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactopyranosyl groups, respectively.
A glycosylglucose that is D-glucopyranose in which the hydroxy group at position 4 has been converted into the corresponding alpha-D-galactoside.
A glucotriose composed of alpha-D-glucopyranose, alpha-D-glucopyranose and beta-D-glucofuranose residues joined in sequence by 1->6 glycosidic linkages.
A glucotriose that is D-glucopyranose in which the hydroxy groups at positions 4 and 6 have been converted into the corresponding beta-D-glucopyranoside and alpha-D-glucopyranoside, respectively.
A glucooligosaccharide consisting of six alpha-D-glucopyranosyl residues and a D-glucopyranosyl residue connected in sequence by (1->6) glycosidic linkages.
An inulobiose in which the anomeric centre has beta-configuration.
A 4-hydroxymethylzymosterol in which the hydroxymethyl group at position 4 has alpha-configuration.
A 4-formylzymosterol in which the formyl group at position 4 has alpha-configuration.
A trimethoxyflavone that is myricetin in which the hydroxy groups at position 3, 3' and 5' have been replaced by methoxy groups.
2'-deoxyytidine in which one of the exocyclic amino hydrogens is substituted by an acetyl group.
A pyrimidone that is cytosine bearing an N(4)-acetyl substituent.
A trimethoxyflavone that is myricetin in which the hydroxy groups at position 7, 3' and 5' have been replaced by methoxy groups.

A linear tetrasaccharide derivative consisting of a 6-O-[(2-aminoethoxy)(hydroxy)phosphoryl-alpha-D-mannose residue, two alpha-D-mannose residues and one beta-D-glucosamine residue, linked sequentially (1->2), (1->6) and (1->4), with the glucosamine residue linked glycosidically to a 6-sulfanylhexyl group.

A dimethoxyflavone that is quercetin in which the hydroxy groups at position 3 and 3' have been replaced by methoxy groups. It has been isolated from several plant species and exhibits anti-bacterial and anti-cancer properties.

A tetramethoxyflavone that is myricetin in which the hydroxy groups at positions 3, 3', 4' and 5' are replaced by methoxy groups. It is isolated from Bridelia ferruginea, a subtropical medicinal plant widely used in traditional African medicine.

A dimethoxyflavone that is kaempferol in which the hydroxy groups at position 3 and 4' have been replaced by methoxy groups. It is a component of bee glue and isolated from several plant species including Tanacetum microphyllum.
A secondary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of herquline B resulting from the protonation of the secondary amino group; Major species at pH 7.3.
Any branched trisaccharide consisting of D-galactopyranose having an L-fucosyl residue at the 2-position and a D-galactosyl residue at the 3-position.

A dimethoxyflavone that is kaempferol in which the hydroxy groups at position 4' and 7 have been replaced by methoxy groups. It is a component of bee glue and has been isolated from several plant species including Betula exilis, Zingiber mekongense and Alpinia flabellata.

A secondary ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of one of the amino groups of (1S,7R,8R,14S)-15,17-diazatetracyclo[12.2.2.1(3,7).1(8,12)]icosa-3(20),12(19)-diene-6,9-dione. This is compound 7 of pmid:27690412.
This is the major tautomer at pH 7.3 of compound 13 of pmid:27690412

A linear pentasaccharide derivative consisting of four alpha-D-mannose residues and one beta-D-glucosamine residue, linked sequentially (1->2), (1->2), (1->6) and (1->4), with the glucosamine residue linked glycosidically to a 6-sulfanylhexyl group.

A linear pentasaccharide derivative consisting of an alpha-D-mannose residue, a 6-O-[(2-aminoethoxy)(hydroxy)phosphoryl-alpha-D-mannose residue, two further alpha-D-mannose residues and one beta-D-glucosamine residue, linked sequentially (1->2), (1->2), (1->6) and (1->4), with the glucosamine residue linked glycosidically to a 6-sulfanylhexyl group.
